<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920120-0057</DOCNO><DOCID>920120-0057.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Mercom Inc.:   Cable TV Company Expects   $7.6 Million Net Loss in '91</HL><DATE>01/20/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4</SO><CO>   MEROC</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)</IN><NS>EARNINGS PROJECTIONS (ERP)</NS><RE>MICHIGAN (MI)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Mercom Inc., a Michigan cable televison company, said itexpects a net loss in 1991 of approximately $7.6 million, or$3.19 a share, on revenue of about $11 million.   The company said its &quot;preliminary estimate&quot; includedunusual and nonrecurring charges of approximately $5.2million, or $2.19 a share, because of restructuring costs,legal costs and the costs of a proxy fight waged last year byMercom's new managers. C-Tec Corp. a Wilkes-Barre, Pa.,telephone and cable television company, won control of Mercomin December after a lengthy proxy fight. C-Tec officers arenow running Mercom.</LP><TEXT>   Charles E. Parente, Mercom's newly appointed chiefexecutive officer, said that Mercom faces &quot;significantchallenges&quot; in the months ahead, including the need to secureadequate long-term financing.   As of Dec. 31, Mercom's liabilities exceeded its assets by$11 million, the company said. James Bogdan, Mercom's chieffinancial officer, said it was not unusual for cabletelevision companies to have negetive net worth because ofhigh start-up costs, but that $11 million was high for acompany this small. Mercom has 33,000 suscribers insoutheastern Michigan.</TEXT></DOC>